description.text: these landing gear provide are longer to provide more space for camera and gimbal, they are also moved out to the edges of the frame to open up the space beneath the quad. the wide stance is also makes it MUCH more easy to land, if its windy or what not. i used old graphite rod from some old arrows (like bow and arrow arrows), they are extremely light and strong. some hose or heatshrink can be used for rubber feet, or you could print something. the gear removes in seconds so its easy to pack up the quad. much quicker than the threaded screws used to secure the stock landing gear. scale the parts up 10x, the export to stl had a mm-->cm conversion problem. the mounts press into the existing screw bosses and are held on using cable ties, no modification to the frame is required. on a hard crash landing i snapped a cable tie once when the leg was forced sideways.... which is more convenient than breaking the frame.

title: Robo 3D R1+Plus 60mm Hobbed Bolt Fitting with Wiring Arm
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text:
I needed to replace my extruder's stock M8x50mm hobbed bolt. That size does not seem to be widely available, but I found a few 60mm ones. I also recently had to remove the zip ties from the extruder's wiring, so I wanted a way to better secure all that. The combination of those issues resulted in this design.

The bearing and washer are taken from the gear side of the existing hobbed bolt and reused. With the wiring zip tie removed, I can't see any purpose in continuing to use a bearing as a spacer on that side, so it is replaced by a printed part. The washer provides a metal contact surface between the printed spacer and the bearing housed in the extruder body. For the part on the wiring side, the bearing is inserted mid-print so that it is encased in the part. I added two more washers between the bearings on that side to give it a really solid feel when tightening up the bolt, though you could probably get by with one or even zero. It's a bit tricky getting washers in there and there's just enough contact surface on the part that the washer(s) could be unnecessary.

Anyway, seems to work just fine, my prints are looking better than ever with a new hobbed bolt in there, and I didn't have to overspend or wait for international shipping. I'm happy with it and I hope you are too.

Printer Brand:

Robo 3D

Printer:

R1 ABS + PLA Model

Rafts:

No

Supports:

No

Resolution:

0.2

Infill:

33%

Notes:

On the piece for the wiring side, pause the print at layer 42 to drop in the bearing. I didn't have great luck getting the next layer to adhere to the bearing, but I only made the one attempt since it did eventually build up enough material to hold. I think a bit of glue stick around the edge of the bearing's upper surface might have done OK. That or maybe check into how people go about printing fidget spinners.

Notes:

print it with the connector UP to avoid supports

wiring

cut two pieces of thin wire (1mm)
solder one end into the SMA connector on the ground ring
then solder the second one into the central pin
bend both of them into opposite directions
cut precisely the tip so that they will be 86 mm length measured from the outside of the sma connector

antenna cover

insert the tips of the wires into the frame
gently slide them so that the connector fits in place
epoxy glue the cover (don't put too much glue if you want to be able to reuse the connector)

description.text:
This is a 4x3 Lego block made with Fusion 360 and Illustrator... I made this to be milled on my XCarve.

I haven't made it yet but I will update this files if I make any corrections

This is a cup holder made for NA & NB Miatas. I drink a lot of 16oz cans, which tend to spill everywhere inside the center console of my NB1. The cup holder is designed specifically for cans but you could fit some cups and bottles in too, or adapt the ring yourself to accommodate whatever you like.

I used a modified version of teejay187's four-spoke vent design for my vent piece. They've got a few other vent designs, a very cool race dash, and some other Miata related things. so go check out their page.

Assembly Instructions

First, remove the vent from your car and take it apart. you should have three pieces, the vent ball, a sleeve that it sits in, and a bezel that holds it in place. Then you can test fit the vent portion of the cup holder in the sleeve.

Glue:
I found E6000 works very well on the PLA I print with, so that's what I used. if you want to do a nice job of this, put the bezel in between the vent and the ring BEFORE you glue. this way, you won't have to break the bezel like I did.

Metal "Hook":
I used some 1" x 1/8" aluminum bar stock bent into this sort of hook shape to act as the base. To install it I used some 3M double sided foam tape. I'm using the scotch brand stuff for mounting photos, which worked fine, but I think their outdoor mounting tape would have been a better option. once it's stuck down, you can drill and screw the hook down for some extra security. I wouldn't trust the tape alone because of the heat cycling and condensation.

Here you can see the cup holder already glued together sitting in the sleeve, and my broken bezel. I forgot to take a picture before gluing, but it's nothing complicated. Here's the hook, 1" x 1/8" bar stock, bend it to whatever shape you like. I designed mine to catch the concave portion of the can, which is why it's hook shaped. The Tape. you can see I've already drilled holes in my hook for screws later, I would recommend doing this before taping.

description.text:

Originally designed for a scrollable background on stage. Works as a turntable or lazy susan.

Feature video shot of the bearing parts... on the bearing turntable - just mounted to a wooden plate and a sheet of paper: https://youtu.be/D4AIwcGMFz4

Included 3 parts:
lower race
cage
upper race

Can be used with 2 lower races as well. Upper race includes a little guard so it does not slip away.
Load the balls by inserting a ball in every 2nd hole, put on the upper race, then turn 180° and load remaining balls,, put on lower race.
Upper and lower race include counter-synced screw holes.

Can hold at least the weight of 2 humans, in PLA.

I wanted to monitor the voltage and current of my printer and therefore I made a small box that included a voltmeter and ampere meter and some switches.

The box fits next to the standard display when it is moved to the side.
For mounting the Switchbox on the Printer 4 T-nuts M3 and 4 screws M3x10mm are required.
And for the Frontcover you need 4 M3 Screws 5-10mm lengh.

The display shows the voltage from the power supply and the current consumption of the entire printer. For this purpose, a shunt was installed in the power supply which allows currents up to 50A to be displayed.

The two buttons next to the display are for the LED lighting and to cancel the printing. (Killswich). This is controled by a raspberry pi with the enclosure plugin for octoprint.
With the switch on the site, the mains voltage is switched on and off. This make it easier to switch the printer on and off because the original switch is on the back of the printer ...

Things i have used:

  • DROK YB27VA-50A Dual Display Digital Voltmeter/Ammeter, DC 0V-100V/50 Amp, +50 Amp/75mV Shunt
  • 1 round Switch 21mm cutout diameter (on/off)
  • 2 Pushbuttons 18mm cutout diameter (normally open)
  • Some wires and Crimpconnectors

The .skp files are also to download when someone want to redraw the cutout diameter for the display or the switches.

title: CR-10 | CR-10S | BondTech BMG E3D V6 + EZABL Mount V2

description.text:
UPDATE 2/26/2018
I have designed a 40mm fan mount to accommodate the Noctua 40mm Fan (NF-A4x10 FLX). The Noctua fan reduced the ambient noise on the CR-10S from around 49-51 dB to around 39-40 dB. I fits snug enough, but is still free to rotate slightly around the E3D heatsink.

I printed this in NylonX for its flexibility, but I believe all materials should work as well, but I have not tested them.

Thanks to Sean for the Noctua 40mm fan shroud GrabCAD model and to JuanCR for the E3D V6 GrabCAD model!

This new mount assembly was designed to restore full use of the CR-10/CR-10S build area. I was not thrilled with the previous design which eliminated almost 15-20 mm in X and Y so I went back to re-design this unit to fit as close to the stock CR-10 extruder assembly as possible to re-gain this area back. The Z-Axis will also improve as the long E3D hotend will be closer to the bottom of the X-Axis carriage as compared to the stock assembly.

Only Parts/Hardware needed

Extruder mount screws for Bondtech assembly (should be included in kit)

2X M4x0.7mm x 22mm long screws for the blower fan mount

50mm x 15mm Blower Fans
https://www.amazon.com/gp/product/B071WMHNG5/ref=oh_aui_detailpage_o05_s00?ie=UTF8&psc=1

EZABL Sensor
https://www.th3dstudio.com/product/ezabl-kit-direct-wire/

Small Nema 17 Stepper Motor
https://www.omc-stepperonline.com/hybrid-stepper-motor/nema-17-bipolar-18deg-18ncm-255ozin-07a-29v-42x42x25mm-4-wires-17hs10-0704s.html

Assembly Instructions:

Mount the Bondtech Extruder Carriage part to the CR-10 X-axis carriage first. Then install the blower fan, blower fan duct, and angle brace next using the two M4 screws. This will give more room to install these components without the stepper motor getting in the way. Last step is to install the stepper motor and BondTech extruder on the mount to complete the setup. Make sure to orient the heat block so that the nozzle is pointing closer to the front of the mount and thermistor/heater cartridge wires are exiting toward the bondtech assembly side

Printer:

Creality CR-10S

Rafts:

Yes

Supports:

Yes

Resolution:

0.2mm - 0.25mm

Infill:

10% - 20%

Notes:

Suggested Materials (High Temp Resistant):

PETG (Material I chose)
Nylon
ABS

It is recommended to use rafts on both parts for this assembly. The dimensions are critical for these parts so preventing any warp while printing is required.

I was able to successfully print the Extruder Carriage without supports anywhere, but I would suggest to add at least 4 top and bottom layers for the section that the stepper motor mounts for added rigidity and flatness.

On the Blower Fan Mount, I used supports only under the first portion of the duct to ensure the remaining overhang layers would print correctly, but depending on layer height and speeds, the results could vary.

Marlin Firmware Settings for ABL Sensor Position
X_PROBE_OFFSET_FROM_EXTRUDER 0 // X offset: -left +right [of the nozzle]
Y_PROBE_OFFSET_FROM_EXTRUDER -42 // Y offset: -front +behind [the nozzle]
Z_PROBE_OFFSET_FROM_EXTRUDER 0 // Z offset: -below +above [the nozzle]

// Set the boundaries for probing (where the probe can reach).
LEFT_PROBE_BED_POSITION 45
RIGHT_PROBE_BED_POSITION 255
FRONT_PROBE_BED_POSITION 45
BACK_PROBE_BED_POSITION 255

I decided to go back to step one in determining where the best placement for this extruder assembly would be so that I could reclaim the 300 sq. mm build area back. The obvious choice would be to place the assembly so the E3D hotend would be in as close as the stock location for the CR-10 as possible. The challenges are since I will use the Direct Extruder setup, the stepper motor must be raised higher than the carriage in order to bring that long E3D hotend as close to the bottom of the X-Axis carriage as possible.

Factors that needed to be verified were clearance of the extruder motor when it hits the X-Axis endstop bracket, and if the higher Center of Gravity of the components caused any issues with print quality.

In the end, I am very happy with the results and am glad to share my work! Happy Printing!

author: castro905

title: 3D Printed Pulse Energizer For Radiant Energy (5.125" Diameter)
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text:
https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Yi_3kPt-0eY&t=75s
https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=5Z763gdGOG8
https://1drv.ms/f/s!Apbifed6cvBmbjLYdzp4fQzMWGA
This video shows running it up to destruction.
https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=QPrsLvrOsKw&t=27s
Pulse motors typically do not get hot when wired correctly. They are not to be confused with DC Brushless motors which use advanced circuits to pulse energy through the coils. This pulse motor represents a tool to experiment with. I use the Bedini SSG circuit to pulse this energizer. You can go here: http://www.energyscienceforum.com/forumdisplay.php?f=48 to learn about that technology. It is a simple circuit that most people can learn to put together in a short period of time. This company offers a Bedini SSG Circuit kit that will work with this energizer: http://teslagenx.com/kits/tx-sg4tub.html?category=kits|pcb. You can use other methods to pulse if you desire.

Disclaimer: Build and experiment at your own risk. Catastrophic failure of parts spinning at high speed can cause damage to property, injury, or even death. There is an electrical function with this experimental device. Do not attempt without experience working with electricity. Do not operate around equipment that is sensitive to electromagnetic frequencies.

parts list:

        the magnetic wire is your choice
        transistor(s):  the slots are made to fit the mjl21194g transistor  
        It uses a double stack of the popular sized ceramic magnets (1-7/8" X 7/8" X 3/8") like these :https://www.harborfreight.com/pack-of-2-ceramic-block-magnets-97504.html
        all bolts are 6-32.  For the inner motor you can use 3/8" length at every point.
        for the motor housing you can use 1" to 1.125" at every point
        It is important to note here that nonmagnetic hardware (brass, stainless steel, nylon) allows for the best performance.
        shaft:  1/2" X at least 6"  stainless steel or aluminum 
        magnet rotor set screw: 6-32 X 5/8" (note:  you will need to grind a flat spot on the shaft or drill a hole in it for the set screw)
        bearings:  It is recommended to use at least ABEC-5 like these: http://www.vxb.com/SR8-2RS-Ceramic-ABEC-5-1-2-x1-1-8-x5-16-inch-p/kit13852.htm  I bought and used cheaper bearings for the demonstration model like these: http://www.vxb.com/R8-2RS-Sealed-Bearing-1-2-x1-1-8-x5-16-inch-p/kit7478.htm

I used pla for this motor. It was designed to print .01" larger at each location for the bolts, magnets, and bearings to compensate for shrinkage. print settings where .2mm for layer height, 1.2mm walls, .8mm top and bottom layers and 20% - 30% for the infill.

Three printable part files were added to be able to use 8mm rods and skateboard bearings. These bearings are tried and true: https://bonesbearings.com/bones-reg-swiss-skateboard-bearings-8-pack It is recomended to use at least ABEC-5 bearings and a non-magnetic shaft for optimal performance.

2/24/2018 I added a magnet cover for additional support. This should add some safety when spinning at higher rpm's. A better option would be a fiberglass or carbon fiber layer. This should also be accompanied with 100% infill on the rotor for high speed experiments. Also don't forget to glue your magnets in place. I like Gorilla Glue. It seems to handle shock and vibration the best. Make sure you use water or it won't set properly.

2/25/2018 I added some small panels to help keep the "Window" wire off of the rotor. I recommend using Loctite (5 sec) Super Glue. Just dab a little on each end and attach them to the center.

2/26/2018 added 1/16" shaft spacers which may be needed to provide a snug fit for the rotor between the bearings

3/01/2018 added some slightly more robust parts for those that want to run it up to higher rpm's. The trade off here is stronger parts but more plastic + longer print times. I still recommend printing at higher infills (greater than 30%) and glueing your magnets in place. It is also still recommended to create at least 1.2mm walls. These parts are listed as #1, #2, and #3. They are still interchangeable with the other listed parts. Sorry, these are for 8mm rods and bearings only.

title: Dragonlock compatible blocking clip (blocks hill_side parts from falling downwards)

description.text:
This clip is like a mirror version of the original Core_Shim. It prevents side parts from falling down and gives mountain structures increased durability.

What it helps with:

  1. your mountain sides don‘t slide down anymore.

  2. You don‘t need a blocking clip for every mountain core because the ones next to it also block cores from sliding down. That saves you a few tiles every mountain structure.

  3. Since the blocking bottom hexes also seem to give the whole structure more rigidity single caps next to mountain cores don’t fall off anymore, at least with my prints. That is very cool.

  4. Since caps-only tiles now have a way of not letting sides slide, you can come up with fun things to slice on 1/2 inch mountain side parts and put them next to core caps to get some nice lvl 0 terrain (new). I was thinking about cutting caps a bit more so they are more plain, but since I would have to adjust all kinds of parts I stuck with level 0 (ground level) special tiles like woods, rough or stuff like that will be a little bit higher than the ground.

I personally use this for Battletech hills.

author: Rrohloff97

title: Customizable Sports Jersey Keychain
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text: I made these for some “hockey buffs.” The .stl file has no text emboss/engraving, so that you can add your own (learning Customizer is still on my todo list, sorry!).
NGSS

Sports Jersey by Arfurware is a good free TrueType font for the lettering.

I printed the jersey’s black base and yellow top using a single-extruder Wanhao i3 Plus and Simplify3D. There’s a helpful video on how to print multi-colour here: https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=XiwUAZXptPs

I ran out of time to print the top (black) lettering in a 3rd layer, and just used a black permanent marker which sort of worked ok. Not sure how well a thin layer of black filament would hold on a keychain anyway.

Note at the “keychain” size that I printed these (50-ish mm wide and high), I think I had to use a 0.2mm nozzle to produce the fine letter strokes to fit 6 characters across the back. YMMV with a typical 0.4mm nozzle, so test printing those last few (top) lettering layers on your machine first.

Hopefully you’re not trying to fit something like “Brackenborough” on your design :)

Extruding/cutting/embossing text is one of the earliest things many people learn when starting with 3D printing.

This model provides a base to put your own text on and easily create something personalised.

Sized for a keychain, it’s reasonably quick to print – especially if you keep it simple and only use 1 colour. You can also simplify the exercise by only adding the “emboss” lettering on the top of the print, skipping the “engrave” lettering in the print’s base.

Students will also learn some of the constraints of 3D printing – specifically how print nozzle size affects the level of detail you can print.

As noted above, you can also “post-process” your 3D output by manually colouring the letters with a marker. Many jewellers will manually burnish, patine, oxidise, etc. what they’ve 3D printed in metal for a unique hand-crafted look (see here, here and here for some examples). The simple colouring analogy helps students to practice that idea for themselves.

• 3D design software and printer
  • Free Sports Jersey by Arfurware TrueType font installed if you want “authentic” jersey lettering
  • 1 filament colour – or multiple if you have the time and want the complexity/experience
  • Dark permanent marker if you want a simpler multi-colour project

title: Venturi Air Intake for Aquarium Pump
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text:
Venturi air mixing nozzle for a protein skimmer pump in my aquarium. This one is designed to be a snug press-fit around a 32mm diameter x 8mm deep circular pump inlet (such as on the Syncra Sicce PSK1000 Skimmer Pump that I happen to have), and accepts a 10mm (3/8") flexible air hose connection.

No actual photos because I printed it and immediately installed it into my aquarium sump. Happy to report it works exceptionally well.

That said, unless you have the same or a very similar pump, this specific fitting isn't likely to work for you. I chose the Syncra Sicce PSK1000 Skimmer Pump because I needed to replace my failed pump on my protein skimmer for a 300-gallon saltwater aquarium and this one appeared to be a good tradeoff between price and performance on Amazon. (I wasn't willing to pay the ridiculous price for an original equipment pump and was therefore trusting my judgment and tinkering skills to save the day.) Long story short -- if you have the same pump, or are willing to get the right pump, this may work for you.

If you are an aspiring CAD designer who needs a venturi intake, consider using this design as the basis for your own design. They are not that hard to design... basically a sketch of a bunch of concentric circles, a bunch of extrusions of various lengths, and some fillets to blend it all nicely together. I designed this one in Fusion 360 in about 30 minutes.

One variable you may need to play with if you design your own is the degree of constriction on the water intake in the center. More constriction just before the air inlet creates more of a pressure drop, which will suck in more air, but will also reduce your total water flow. The optimal choice will depend on how powerful your pump is.

Printer Brand:

Prusa

Printer:

i3 MK2S

Rafts:

No

Supports:

Yes

25%

Notes:

Print with a thick perimeter for reasonable air- and water-tightness. It doesn't have to be completely airtight and water-tight to work well, but you don't want ridiculous amounts of leakage. Use fine detail settings for smoother water flow (better efficiency) and good resolution of the details.

Needs a small support (on base plate only) for the little air hose connector that sticks off to the side. Doesn't need any other supports if you orient it correctly.

author: Chrlee

description.text:
Introduction:

Introduction video: https://youtu.be/maQO2Yl2V8M

It was my good friend Scott that got me interested in 3D printed RC tanks.
He sent me a couple of youtube links with very cool tanks.

I was inspired by the "RC Speed tank" by Bryant87
https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2024364

and also "RC Tank" by Staind
https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2414983

I though they were really cool, like Terrascout nerf tanks on steroids.
But i wanted a enclosed tank, more resistant to weather, for future robotics FPV projects.
So i started drawing my on tank in Fusion 360. I started from scratch so my parts will not be compatible with the other tanks.

About my design:

My goals was to have it enclosed, have as few non 3d printed parts as possible, have a simple design that is easily printed with as little support material as possible.

Everything is designed around the wheel screws. The screws holds the wheels, act as hinges, mounts the battery tray, and locks the covers. I have even made a small tool to help when working with the screws.

The design is also modular. The battery holder can easy be redesigned to hold different batteries. The covers can be redesigned to hold camera, have more ventilation etc.

The bottom and the covers are designed to be printed on the side, that is why the nut holes are angled, so that no support is needed.

The track segments doesn't need screws and nuts, they are put together by pressfitting
cut to length pieces of 3mm nylon filament. The track segments also have a slot in them, that is for being able to fit different grip insert, like a TPU insert for more traction on slippery surfaces, or sharp teeth for more outdoor traction.

I have included a step file :-)

Things you will need:

2x motor and esc combo, 80T
https://www.banggood.com/540-Motor-60A-ESC-Carbon-Brushed-110-RC-Crawler-Shaft-3_175mm-RC-Car-Parts-p-1187553.html

2x Zippy Compact 3700mAh 3s batteries (or your own battery of choice)
https://hobbyking.com/en_us/zippy-compact-3700mah-3s-25c-lipo-pack.html

24x 8x22x7mm Ball Bearings (standard skateboard bearings)
https://www.banggood.com/10pcs-ABEC-7-608ZZ-8x22x7mm-Ball-Bearings-Deep-Groove-Ball-Bearing-p-1185033.html

2x 11T M1 5mm Pinion Gear
https://hobbyking.com/en_us/11t-5mm-m1-hardened-steel-pinion-gear-1pc.html
and
2x 5mm to 3.2mm pinion adapter
https://www.banggood.com/HOBBYWING-Motor-Axle-3_17mm-To-5mm-Change-over-Shaft-Adapter-p-927457.html (might even be possible to print)

or

2x 12T 3.2mm Pinion Gear
https://www.conrad.se/St%e5lkugghjul-Reely-523-3,2-STAHL-Modul-typ-1.0-Borrdiameter-3.2-mm-Antal-t%e4nder-12.htm?websale8=conrad-swe&pi=240362

12x M6 70mm Hex bolt
12x M6 Nut
8x M3 10mm screw (for the motors)
2x velcro strap for holding batteries

3mm nylon filament (or other types of 3mm filament)
http://taulman3d.com/618-features.html

Your own RC radio and receiver, preferably on that supports tank mixing.
https://hobbyking.com/en_us/frsky-2-4ghz-accst-taranis-x9d-plus-digital-telemetry-radio-system-mode-2.html

A couple of zipties
Battery connectors

How to print:

I have printed everything in regular PLA.
Track segments are printed with 100% infill everything else with 20%.
The covers and bottom are designed to be printed on its side, a little brim is a good idea.

notanks_v1_bottom_wheel.stl need support material.
notanks_v1_front_cover.stl needs touching buildplate support

Things you need to print multiple of:

2x notanks_v1_drive_wheel_55t.stl if you use 12t pinion for motor.
2x notanks_v1_drive_wheel_56t.stl if you use 11t pinion for motor.

82x notanks_v1_track.stl
8x notanks_v1_bottom_wheel.stl
2x notanks_v1_front_wheel.stl
24x notanks_v1_wheel_insert.stl
2x notanks_v1_outside.stl
2x notanks_v1_inside.stl (mirror one when printing)

How to assemble:

  1. Tool
    Print the included tool, it makes the job building easier then using a wrench. It is also great to have when out in the field driving.

  2. Wheels:
    Two ball bearings are press fitted into each wheels, a vise is a good tool for that.
    A wheel insert is then fitted into each ball bearing in the wheels, that is two per wheel.
    Be in mind that if you have chosen to use the 11 teeth motor pinion gear you will need the 56 teeth drive wheel, if you have chosen the 12 teeth motor gear then you will need the 55 teeth drive gear.

  3. Bottom, Cover and sides:
    The nuts are press fitted into the holes using a screw from the other side to drag them in.

  4. Motors:
    Attache pinion gears (and adapters) to motors. Screw the motors to the inside parts.

  5. Sides:
    Put the long bolts into the outside parts, put the wheels on the bolts. Front wheel in the front and drive wheel on top. Put the inside part with the motor on the bolts and screw in the drive wheel bolt.

  6. Bottom
    Screw the now assembled sides onto the bottom part. Before thightening the screws, insert the rc holder part, between the slots in the insides.

  7. Covers
    Screw on the front and back cover.

  8. The tracks:
    The track segments is put together by pressing in pieces of 3mm nylon filament.
    41 segments per track,. When mounting the tracks it is easiest to remove the back wheel push it forward and then tighten the track when the back wheel is pushed back and mounted. It is going to be very thigh first, but loosens a little bit over time when driving. But you might even want to start with 42 segments per track. For easy disassemble you can leave one filament piece a bit longer sticking out some millimeter so that it can be grabbed by pliers.

  9. Battery holder:
    Unscrew the two bottom middle bolts a little bit, mount the battery holder and fasten it by screwing in the bolts again. Attach a velcro strap to the slots in the battery holder for holding batteries.

  10. Electronics:
    Solder the wires to the motors. Battery connectors to the ESC:s. Mount the ESC:s and receivers onto the rc holder using zipties. Connect wires and fasten the wires to the holder with zipties.

  11. RC:
    Program your radio with a good tank mix, go out and have fun.

Warnings / Future upgrades

Caution when driving in the winter:

Snow can build up and get the tracks stuck. That is what happened to me once, i was >using a 35T motor and when the track got stuck the motor draw to much current and >burned up. In future upgrades I will make the inside and outside part bigger to cover the >wheels completely to limit snow from getting in to the tracks.

Heat:

When i have tested the tank it is in the middle of the Swedish winter, with temperatures >blow zero degree Celsius. If driving in warmer locations, perhaps ventilation for the motors >and escs are required. I have thought about making changes to front and back cover to >allow mounting a 40mm fan on each side, for better cooling, and if so the inlet will be >angled backwards to prevent dirt from getting in, but that is for later considerations.

Drive wheel:

I have experimented with having the driving on the front wheel, an even on the front and >top wheel at the same time, but it seams having just the top wheel is less sensitive to dirt >and stuff locking up the tracks. I have seen a design on thingiverse that have a planetary >gear built into the drive wheel, that might be wort a try in the future.

FPV:

I am thinking of making a camera turret on the front cover, and putting in a rasperry pi zero and a 4g modem and some other electronics, and drive it around like a robot..

title: Magnetic filament holder for Prusa MK2
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text:
A filament spool holder with filament guide for the Prusa MK2 3d printer - we have been using it for a long time, feel free to adapt it to other printer models.

To get the parts shown in the first picture print 2 x part A, 2 x part B and 1 x part C, combine with the following materials as shown in the other pictures. The hexagon pattern is not part of the design, it is the infill pattern. The filament used to print the model shown is PLA Extrafill "Vertigo Grey".

4x 10x10x5mm N52 magnets
3x 14mm M3 bolts
3x M3 nuts
2x 8x22x7mm ball bearings
1x 100mm long 8mm diameter steel rod
1x 5cm 3mm inner diameter 4mm outer diameter teflon tube
Some superglue

Instructions:
1: Print the parts.
2: Remove supports (if used).
3: Insert magnets and glue them in place (make sure you have aligned them properly before gluing them in place).
4: Glue the rod to the ball bearings as shown.
5: Glue the rod with ball bearings to part A.
6: Slide teflon tube into part C.
7: Place parts B and C on the 3D printer.
8: Slide the M3 nuts into the nut traps and screw in the bolts.
9: Put a spool of filament on the rod and place it on the holder, slide the free end of the filament into the filament holder.

title: Carpet Tack/Anchor
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text:
For those rug-on-top-of-another-rug decorating situations: This is an anchor designed to secure an area rug on top of plush wall-to-wall carpet. The accordion-style feet press down into the plush carpet while the small pointy tacks stick up into the base of the area rug.

Approx 10cm square. Two outer corners have been removed to enable printing without supports.

Works reasonably well in our rug-on-rug situation.

When laid on the ground without any rug on top, works well as a painful object to step on in the middle of the night.

Resolution:

fine (for the pointy tacks)

Infill:

no

Notes:

Probably best with a plastic that can flex a little bit like PETG, nylon, ABS, or maybe TPU. Using too brittle of a plastic will probably lead to cracking and breaking of the tiny tacks when someone steps on it.

Does not need supports as long as your printer does a decent job bridging.

description.text:
Carriage for E3Dv6 hotend for my xBot-Medium printer.
Also including BLTouch this is physically/mechanically fully compatible with Ultimaker 2/3 axes.

There is enough room for easy usage of TL-Feeder.

Using a 30mm fan, mounted on the rear side, to cool the Heatsink of the hotend, and 2 other 30mm fans to cool the objects printed.
If you are using my xBot printer (opens my blog), there is room for 40mm fans in future models.

Files
You have the main parts in 2 versions:

  • One wiht and one without the xBot text.
    And 3 different "clamp" parts.
  • 2 of these are for people with BLTouch, where one is with build in support and the other is not. You do need more support for both, but the added support is just to retain the area up against the hotend.
  • The 3rd is a Clamp without mounting area for BLTouch.

Yes

Infill:

40

Notes:
  • Print using ABS or similar.
  • Print using 3 perimeters and 40% infill.
  • Remember you might need to scale your model 3% or something like that if your ABS is shrinking.
  • If you are using Igus bushings as I am, then you do not want them squeezed.
  • I recommend printing it lying down, as it is, and use support "Touching Buildplate only" + a "Support Interface" to make it nice and smooth on the rear side

description.text:
Print-in-place caster wheel that I designed as an experiment. Works better than you'd expect although it needs some breaking-in time to smooth out the internal plastic ball bearings.

The swivel shaft is printed separately and clicked into place. Shaft diameter is designed to be a snug press-fit into a 9mm receptacle.

Wheel diameter is approximately 43mm. Wheel rolls freely on 12 internal ball bearings that print in place.

It is shockingly strong and can easily tolerate a working load of 50 lbs or more (after being broken in). In any real world situation, the first thing to fail will be the swivel shaft, which is likely to crack when the wheel hits some kind of divot or obstacle and incurs a large shear (sideways) loading. If you actually intend to use this wheel on an office chair or something, be sure to read the print notes below.

Supports:

No

Resolution:

fine

Infill:

dense

Notes:

Print with the flat side of the wheel facing down onto the print bed. Does not need supports.
Use fine print resolution to make the bearings as round and smooth as possible.

If you actually intend to use the wheel under real-world load conditions, print it with very thick walls (quad ply or more) and dense infill for high strength.

Important: The swivel shaft is the weakest link and needs to be printed as strongly as possible. Print it lying down horizontally for maximum layer strength. (It has a flat side intended for this purpose.) Print it solid or at least with a very high number of perimeter layers.

Consider printing with slightly higher than normal print temperatures to get extra strong layer bonding.

After printing, click the shaft into the receptacle on the wheel. It should swivel freely once clicked into place. You will also need to spend some time running the wheel back and forth under moderate load to break in the bearings. It will likely take some elbow grease to initially crack loose the wheel and bearings after printing.

Works best with a tough, slightly flexible filament such as nylon, ABS, or PETG. I used PETG for mine and it worked well.

description.text:
This is in essence a 1:1 "enlarger". It uses a standard 50mm (M39 mount) enlarger lens of your choice to hold your film perfectly for digitizing it with a Sony E-mount camera. The design is semi parametric so you can adjust the lengths of the tubes if you need to remix this for a different lens mount.

The threaded tubes are designed with a buttress thread. This avoids issues when printing the threads as there are no overhangs. The threads are designed on the loose side. If you require them tighter just add some Teflon tape after printing to snug them up.

Make sure to print the parts in a plastic that isn't transparent. It will save you a lot of spray painting.

Glue the swivel lock only to the mount so that the whole decide can be rotated relative to the camera without adjusting the focus.

The film holder itself is designed to be spring loaded using 3mm cap head screws and a compression spring between the nut and film holder. If you don't have a 3mm bolt use a small section of 3mm filament.

The cut away shows the lens installed in a "facing forward" configuration but you may wish to install it facing in the opposite direction as this is more in line with the normal use of an enlarger lens.

description.text:
It is a bit of a shame that the new Transformers Power of the Primes Grimlock does not come with a proper sword. So, I produced this model based on the sword used by the Dinobot combiner Volcanicus as featured in "Transformers: Earth Wars". This model features a 5 mm handle that will plug right into any 5 mm weapon or accessory port. And, the handle is long enough to plug through both the top and bottom "thumbs" on the Volcanicus fists.

The model is intended to be printed in halves (precluding the need to use supports) and then glued together afterward. I printed a couple copies myself, both in ABS, and used "Plastruct Bondene" plastic model cement to stick them together. Acetone or cyanoacrylate (super glue, crazy glue) would also have worked just fine. If you print with PLA, cyanoacrylate will probably be the best choice.

There are two versions of the model included in the downloadable files. Select the one that suits your printer best. The 2-piece version max part length is 151 mm. The 4-piece version max part length is 122 mm. Regardless of which version you print, the final assembled sword will be the same size.

UPDATE! Volcanicus Torso Upgrade Now Available!

I finally got around to finishing version 1 of a torso upgrade for Volcanicus that I've had on my mind for a while now. This upgrade accomplishes two goals: 1) Fill in the empty holes and areas surrounding Grimlock's T-Rex head, and 2) Provide additional stabilization to Grimlock's arms so they don't flop around and un-tab while rotating the combiner arms.

This entire thing can be 3D printed without the need for supports. But, that means some glue assembly of parts will be required after you print them.

Here is an overview of the parts as shown in the picture provided. The part at the 9 o'clock position plugs into the front of the torso and serves as the foundation for the upgrade. I also added a 5 mm hole on each side in case you want to plug in your spare Volcanicus fists. The cosmetic chest filler part at the 3 o'clock position will be glued onto the front of the foundation piece. The two red support tab parts at the 6 o'clock position will be glued onto the sides of the foundation piece to provide support for Grimlock's arms when in torso-mode. And, the part at the 12 o'clock position is just a "blank" chest filler part from which you can carve your very own custom chest design!!

ANOTHER UPDATE!!!

I modified the chest back piece so that the 5 mm holes on the sides now go all the way through the part...this should allow for a more secure fit for the extra fists.

I also came up with a new chest front design (Dinobot V2). This revised design looks a hell of a lot better...in my opinion...and does away with some of the super tiny details that made the original version difficult to print attractively.

Enjoy!

title: Clarinet (work in progress)
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text:
Dimensionally accurate Bb clarinet body. Doesn't have the holes or mount points for keywork yet. Also still missing the cut-out notches for the corks at the joints. Does not include a mouthpiece since any decent player is likely to have their own individual preference.

I used a caliper and set of bore gauges to get the measurements extremely accurately (0.1mm or better). If you printed it, it would play in tune. Measurements were taken from a reasonably high quality name-brand plastic clarinet since I didn't want to risk scratching my nice wood ones with the calipers.

Toughest part to get right was the bell's curvature since there doesn't seem to be any foolproof way to get a compound curve exactly right. I took a series of diameter measurements at various points and interpolated. If you are a good player who for some reason decides to print and play the bell, and it doesn't sound right to you, AND you are pretty sure it's because of poor dimensions and not because you chose for some reason to actually try to play on a 3D printed plastic clarinet bell rather than a real one, let me know.

I will try to do more work on this -- at least getting the tone holes in -- but it's a slow and tedious process. Anyone who wants to do a remix to add the tone holes, feel free and please let me know -- I can provide the source CAD files.

description.text:
Here's a 100Hex based gear kit and the gears work! Thanks to McMaster-Carr for posting 3D files of their mechanical parts, I was able to use real gear geometry in Fusion 360. The base plate has 28 threaded holes located so that the different gears will mate in a number of different combinations. Check out the photos and the gear plan for all the possible combinations.

  • I've included a tool to make assembly easier
  • Make sure you print enough gears and bolts to try all the combinations
  • The longer bolt is used with the hands.
  • Don't tighten the bolts too much or the gears won't turn
  • Be gentle when first trying to turn the gears and don't force them

If you feel really ambitious, print three sets of everything and then mount them on the stand using three bolts from the back. It's possible to connect all the gears across the three base plates.

Please post a photo if you print this in different colors or work out a different gear combination.

Update #1: Here's a short video of the gears in action: https://www.youtube.com/edit?o=U&video_id=wGhTTET9sgY or https://vimeo.com/255257882

Update #2: I've added three new bolt designs with partial threads. These bolts may be tightened down but will leave clearance so the gears can easily spin.

Update #3: New double and triple gears added. Use the partial threaded bolts with these.

Update #4: New YouTube video showing multiple levels of gears https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=f6l_Ru8qeA4

title: Mercedes Benz W168 Bonnet/Hood Stay Latch Retainer

description.text:
The bonnet stay are known to break on these models, making the stay loose in the engine bay potentially causing damage to other components.

This replacement clip is to replace a broken or missing factory stay. It is a little different looking to the factory due to not being an injection molded part like the original.

To install simply insert the top clip hook into the top sheet metal hole at a slight angle so the lip is under the sheet metal, then straighten the clip until the low clip hook 'clicks' and locks into the sheet metal body.

Recommended to be printed in a higher heat range plastic material as this sits in the engine bay above the radiator.

Replaces factory Mercedes Benz EPC/EPAS part number A1688870060 for W168 series A140, A160, A170, A190 and A210 as well as W414 cargo variants.

description.text:
Element board and round tracker for the Gloomhaven board game.

Tested with a 15% Grid pattern infill which may have been a bit overboard.

The round tracker is slightly narrower than the official one to accommodate the 'metal' brackets at the corners. The Element board has holes to accept pegs on the tracker.

Edit 2/12/18: Added a board without the element symbols by request.

Edit: Round Tracker is up! This can be attached to the back of the element board via the pegs (remember to break off the built in supports first!). I toy with the idea of making the element board thinner which would mean the text and symbols would not be as deep. Feedback welcome.

Gloomhaven is copyright to Issac Childres and Cephalofair Games. If they ask for me to remove it, it gets removed, no questions asked.

Never use AutoCAD for 3d work

Once upon a time, Autodesk added 3d tools to AutoCAD and many of us weeped.....because it was so damn clunky and horrid and awful.

Many years later, 2018 (this weekend as of this writing), I tried it again and it was still clunky. Improved, but there are better free 3d tools. ACAD is amazing for 2d work, not so much 3d in my experience.

This was made with ACAD 2017 taking dimensions from the original cutout board, element symbols and font straight from Issac's fantastic free Gloomhaven resource upload.

Next thing will be done in something else....

A medium sized Lizardfolk. The players have crashed their airship into the steaming jungles where the Lizardfolk protect their Tyrant King. The mini would also work well for tailed dragonborn, troglodytes & more!

28Chibi is a new generation of minis made to be printed flat on the bed. Inspired by the likes of DutchMogul's DungeonDoll's and GrumpyRobot's FlatMinis, These:

  • Print quickly and reliably on high- or low-end printers alike.
  • Are sized for 28mm games such as D&D, Pathfinder, Shadowrun, Starwars EofE etc
  • Storage is space efficient and safe due to the flat-pack & peg-and-hole base design (The peg is 2x2mm, so if the included base is not to your liking adding a slightly larger hole to your preferred base is a quick modification.)
  • The hands are designed for modular equipment, and should generally also accept objects designed in the FlatMini style.

The detail steps up in increments of 0.6mm, allowing for a variety of different layer heights to still print these crisply. 0.2mm is my go to, but higher or lower values (such as 0.1, 0.12 or 0.3) all work great too.

Happy Printing!

remixed_from.title: E3Dv6 Bowden X-carriage mount v2 for Prusa i3

description.text:
This is very loosely a remix. I really liked Tech2C's nozzle and fan mounting method. But the carriage was for a Prusa with zip-tied bearings – not really my jam. So I redesigned the whole thing and made it for the M3 screws and nuts that ship with the Anet (assuming you have some left over, the 19mm long ones, at the least).

The back of this thing is made to exactly match the original plate carriage. Except instead of the tapped holes for the x belt clips, I added spaces for nuts. This so I can still use the same x belt tensioner (which I can no longer find on Thingiverse).

The extruder motor is now mounted to my workstation using simple wood screws and the original carriage.

  • Storage is space efficient and safe due to the flat-pack & peg-and-hole base design (The peg is 2x2mm, so if the included base is not to your liking adding a slightly larger hole to your preferred base is a quick modification.)
  • The hands are designed for modular equipment, and should generally also accept objects designed in the FlatMini style.

The detail steps up in increments of 0.6mm, allowing for a variety of different layer heights to still print these crisply. 0.2mm is my go to, but higher or lower values (such as 0.1, 0.12 or 0.3) all work great too.

title: Remix of Baroudeur's I3 Mega Quiet power supply cover

description.text:
I love Barodeur's original design, and I needed a replacement cover that positions the fan opposite the large capacitors in my Anycubic I3 Mega power supply.

Their design had an opening that was too small to fit the Scythe SY1012SL12L (1000 RPM) KAZE JYU SLIM 100mm case fan. In my remix, I've enlarged the opening for the fan by 4MM and included the triangles needed as corner supports into the design. You will need this .STL, along with the fan and Barodeur's "blocage.stl" to complete the build. The cover is a VERY tight fit onto the power supply, and you will have to drill two holes to fasten the blocage.stl part to the cover. I used two M2 bolts and nuts but M3 size will work as well.

Another thing worth mentioning, and it was a surprise to me, is that the fan has a 3 pin connector and the power supply board connector was only two pins. I clipped the yellow wire (RPM, not needed) and had to make a 2 pin Dupont connector to plug the fan in, red wire to + and black to -

remixed_from.title: Creality CR-10 Dial Indicator Mount for Bed Level/Tramming

description.text: This is a remix of CallJoe's "Creality CR-10 Dial Indicator Mount for Bed Level/Tramming" rewritten in OpenSCAD. I am using it with the "Triton 1" Dial Indicator 0.001" Graduation Travel Lug Back White Face" found on Amazon. I added a notch for the part cooler fan and vent slots for the hot end fan. You may have to gently file or scrape the inside edge of the frame if it goes on a little too tight. I also made a split rivet that should be secure enough but be sure to print that at 100% infill. I just got my CR-10S and discovered OpenSCAD only last week so be gentle in your assessment of my coding skills:) I also wrote some gcode to move the gauge around the four corners without dragging the probe along the bed. It was written specifically for my CR-10S so use at your own risk. When it starts it will warn you to remove the gauge and you have to push the button on the CR-10's control panel to continue between each step. I have the X and Y axis moving at maximum speed to speed up the leveling process so consider yourself forewarned. I wrote two versions; The first one, bed_leveling.gcode, moves the nozzle to bed level so you can slip a piece of paper between the nozzle and bed and the second one, elevated_bed_leveling.gcode, just lowers the gauge enough to move the dial but keeps the nozzle well elevated. I tried to program it so the dial should still hit Zero switching between the two versions without having to recalibrate.

comments.text:
i was able to print this just fine, turned out very well, the only problem is that the pin and the slot dont hold the gauge precisely, so it wiggles. There is no accurate way to measure the bed if it can wiggle to and fro. The frame fits snug on the nozzle and the pin fits snug in the hole. but the pin and hole needs to be maybe .5 mm larger. Just the smallest amount of drag on the bed and the wobble will distort your reading.
UPDATE I found out what the wiggle is from, on the back of the indicator when the back lug is, some dial indicators have various raises rims around this lug, the one in this Thing is about 18.5 mm the ones on both of my dials, (digital and regular) are 20 and 20'ish mm
if it sat snug or flush in that hole it would probably not wiggle. so the simplest solution if this hapens to you is to stick a piece of 3m tape on the back...no more wiggle.

remixed_from.author: geoffsim
remixed_from.title: Prusa i3 MK2 Clone 360W 24V PSU Cover

title: Prusa i3 MK2-X Remix with i3 MK3 features

description.text:
Inspired by davtr's Prusa i3 MK2-X, and by Tom Sanladerer's review of the Prusa i3 Mk3 I set about building my own printer from scratch using as many features from the i3 Mk3 as I could. So here it is. Principle features are :-

  • Trinamic TMC2130 drivers which offer advantages of
    • Very quiet operation
    • No end stop switches required. The drivers sense when a limit is reached.
    • No potentiometer adjustments. Currents are software selectable.
    • 256 microsteps.
  • Prusa i3 Mk3 parts used for
    • X carriage- X ends, X carriage front and back, and cable holder.
    • Spool holder. - Remixed for 3030 mount
    • Nozzle blower mount - Remixed to fit an E3d Titan extruder.
    • Nozzle blower duct.
    • Power supply enclosure remixed to fit 3030 mounts with a 360W 12V supply.
  • E3d V6 Hotend
  • E3d Titan extruder (clone)
  • BLTouch bed sensor
  • MKS-Gen control board modified to accept Trinamic TMC2130 drivers.
  • PEI print surface.

X Axis

I like the way cable management is done in the Prusa i3 Mk 3 with most of the cables passing through the X carriage assembly and then being held firmly by the cable holder so I reused the parts from the Prusa github.
I remixed the front part of the X carriage to remove parts for the redundant filament sensor.

I chose to use Igus polymer bushings on the X axis. I sort of regret that choice since I found the Igus bushings were initially loose on the smooth rods, but when compressed in their fittings they became very tight and would bind. In the X carriage the bushings are restrained only by cable ties, and I could eliminate binding by not fastening them very tightly so I kept them. If I were doing it again I would use the carbon impregnated copper bushings I ended up using on the Y axis.

E Axis

Prusa i3 Mk3 uses BondTech gears in its extruder. The gears can be bought from BondTech, but the price was so outrageous I elected instead to use an E3D Titan extruder (in fact I used a cheap Chinese clone). The Titan extruder is 3:1 geared so allowing the use of a lighter and smaller extruder motor which I bought from E3D. I created a mounting plate in OpenScad to fit the Titan/motor assembly to the Prusa Mk3 X carriage. The mount plate also carries a BLTouch bed sensor. I chose to use BLTouch because I had good experience of it on my old printer, and the small Prusa PINDA magnetic sensor is not easily available yet, and the new Prusa magnetic heat bed is not available at all.

The hotend is an E3D V6 using its standard cooling fan. The nozzle blower is mounted on a fitting that screws directly to the front panel of the Titan extruder, and uses the standard Prusa i3 Mk3 nozzle duct which I must say works very well indeed.

Z Axis

I bought stepper motors with integrated lead screws from Amazon quite cheaply. The lead screws are only 250mm, but it all fits and I have 180mm of vertical build height. The caps to stop dust getting into the steppers are from the Prusa github.
Once again I used Igus bushings on the Z axis. Once again I regretted it. It took a lot of easing to stop them binding. Next time I disassemble the Z axis I will replace them with copper bushings.

Y Axis

Heat Bed

For the heat bed I chose one marketed as "HICTOP Aluminum Hot Bed" from ebay. It is larger than most at 220x270mm and has a nice plug in connector with a pre wired cable. It is a lot better than my old heat bed. It is only a pity I ordered this larger heat bed after having already bought my Y rods and 3030 extrusion since I cannot reach the entire surface of the heat bed with the hot end nozzle.
A fibre mat held beneath the heat bed helps speed up heating.

PEI Print Surface

The print surface is a PEI sheet, which is one of the best enhancements over my old printer. Everything sticks to it like crazy I have no issues with adhesion or curling even with very large prints.So far I have tried it with PLA ( 55deg, prints come off easily when PEI cools), PETG(80deg. Prints stick very well. Can be a bit hard to remove them. ) and NinjaFlex (40 deg. Prints stick really well. Often need to put a few drops of alcohol around the print, and then they peel off easily.) I have not tried ABS yet, and do not intend to now I am having so much success with PETG.

Y Rods

The Y rods I bought were actually slightly short at 350mm so I remixed the Y end holders from the RebeliX project so they would fit without being loose. No print area is lost as a result of using the shorter rods.

Y Belt

The Y belt holder is thing 745934 It is adjustable so there is no need to use davtr's adjustable Y idler. Instead I remixed the RebeliX Y idler in OpenScad.

The Y bearing holder is thing 2640562. I chose this because it is fully parametric with OpenScad allowing me to adjust the bearing diameter so it would grip Igus bearings with just the right pressure to stop them binding.
As it happens I eventually gave up with Igus bearings and bought some "linear graphite copper set bearing copper bushing oil self-lubricating bearing" from AliExpress. These were considerably better fitting than the Igus bearings, and a lot quieter than conventional LM8UU linear bearings. Time will tell if they were a good investment or not.

Mechanical

T Plate

An OpenScad file was created for a 'T' plate to join the 3030 extrusion.

Covers

I also created an OpenScad file for an 8mm slot cover which I use to restrain cables running in the slots, and another file for end covers to suit the 'B' Type 3030 aluminium extrusion I had bought.
The slot covers and end covers are intended to be printed in a flexible filament such as Ninjaflex. I do not know how well they would work printed in a more rigid filament.

Spool Holder

The spool holder is the standard Prusa i3 Mk3 spool holder remixed to mount onto a 3030 extrusion. Prusa have not yet uploaded the scad file onto their Github, so it is remixed from the stl file.

PSU enclosure

The PSU I bought from Amazon has dimensions of 50mm deep by 114mm wide which is different to the standard Prusa model, so I remixed one from the Prusa scad file as well as parts of thing 2334901

M6 Hex Nut Cage

Inspired by thing 2612753 by Morpheus61, I created an OpenScad file for an M6 Hex Nut Cage. It was handy when I ran out of the rather expensive 'T-nuts'.

Electronics

Control Board

For the control board I bought an MKS-GEN complete with a Reprap Discount Graphical LCD screen, and Trinamic TMC2130 drivers.
The TMC2130 drivers are a key part of what makes the Prusa i3 Mk3 such a remarkable machine IMO. In the Prusa i3Mk3 they are an integral part of the Einsy controller board. Well the Einsy board is not available to purchase other than with an Original Mk3, but it is possible to upgrade other boards to get most of the Einsy features. This is described in this post and video by Tom Sanladerer.

The TMC2130 drivers I bought were manufactured by Fystec in China rather than the German ones manufactured by Watterott Tom used. They are identical apart from a few rather important differences.

  • The Chinese Fystec drivers came pre soldered so making the trick Tom Sanladerer describes of fitting some of the pins upside down is not possible without desoldering them.

    • In practice this is not a problem since all but one of the pins concerned connect directly to the three header pins on the main board below each driver, and it is easy enough to solder directly to the header pins. The fourth lead connects to nothing other than the unused pin on the TMC2130 driver so it is easy enough to just solder onto there.
  • A more severe problem is that there are three solder jumpers on the underside of the TMC2130 driver board. One large easily visible jumper, and two teeny tiny solder jumpers barely visible with the naked eye. The Fystec manufactured drivers have these jumpers set into "standalone" mode where the TMC2130 loses all of its 'smarts' and acts just like any other driver. In order to enable the SPI bus it is necessary to get out a very fine soldering iron and a magnifying glass and set the jumpers as described here
    Anyone not experienced with a soldering iron would be well advised to buy the Watterott drivers in the first instance.

The MKS-Gen Controller board I used came with a Reprap Discount Graphical LCD which uses some of the same pins required by some of the drivers. So in Configuration_adv.h of the Marlin 1.1.8 firmware I reassigned the X and Y Chip Select pins to use D4 and D5 instead. These pins can be found on the 'Servo' connector of the MKS-Gen. My Configuration.h and Configuration_adv.h files are attached for reference if anyone is struggling to get TMC2130 drivers working.

Having soldered the drivers and PCB correctly, the next challenge is to get them to actually work. TMC2130 drivers support three modes of operation.

  • StealthChop in which the drivers are almost silent, but have reduced torque.
  • SpreadCycle in which they make more noise, but have increased torque.
  • Hybrid mode in which they operate in StealthChop at low speeds, and SpreadCycle at higher speeds.

I wanted to make use of another feature called StallGuard in which the drivers sense when motor load increases such as when an axis hits an endstop so eliminating the need for end stop switches.
StallGuard only works in SpreadCycle mode so Marlin 1.1.8 firmware will switch from StealthChop to SpreadCycle mode while homing. Unfortunately it is currently still buggy and my experience is that homing does not work if the drivers are configured in StealthChop mode, and nothing works well if they are configured in SpreadCycle mode.

My experience was that the only mode in which everything worked reliably is in Hybrid mode.
I had issues in Hybrid mode with steppers missing steps in StealthChop mode (possibly due to binding in my Igus bearings) so my configuration files are set up to switch into SpreadCycle even at low speeds.

After much effort my TMC2130 drivers are now working beautifully. They are very quiet. Homing works without having any end stop switches, and I can really notice the difference in detail I get from 256 interpolated microsteps.

The enclosure for the MKS-Gen board is thing 2072096

LCD Display

The enclosure for the LCD Display is thing 213852. I created an OpenScad file for a mount to fit 3030 extrusion. The mount is in two parts and is spring loaded so itwill remain in the position in which it is put.

LED Lighting

I was really pleased with my new printer and decided to 'pimp it up' as I believe the saying is.
I added a G4 3W LED lamp wedged into the 3030 extrusion at the back for general lighting, and a strip of 25 multicolour WS2812B LEDs inserted into the slot around the Z axis. These strips of LEDs are quite cheap on ebay. I used the waterproof version to avoid any issue with short circuits on the 3030 extrusion. Marlin supports WS2812B so it was only a matter of adding a control lead from an unused servo pin to the input, and a 5V supply from a cheap ebay Buck converter to the power supply pins. (The LEDs draw too much current to use the controller boards 5V supply) I made an OpenScad file of a bracket to hold the Buck converter to the aluminium frame and used copper coins to conduct the heat from the Buck converter down to the Aluminium.

remixed_from.author: ewap
remixed_from.title: Marble Pump to build a Hubelino Marble Machine

description.text:
Part of the Duplo Gears Project. Probably only works with Hubelino plastic marbles (24.3 mm diameter).

I started with the original Marble Pump design by ewap but the parts were too big and the design not as modular as I would like. Also, I wanted to make the pump work with Duplo Gears.

What you need:

  • One or many augers. Just put them on top of each other until you reach your target height.
  • One auger bottom. Alternatively you can use a Duplo Gear if you elevate the pump enough for it to fit below. (The auger bottom part is actually the axle top part generated by the gears script.)
  • One bottom part. Or up to four to lift four marbles in different tracks at the same time. (In this case, use brackets for stabilisation if needed.)
  • An outlet on top. Can't go wrong with right.
  • As many housing parts as you need between these to add up to your target height.

A gear to drive the pump can be put at the bottom but also at the top if that's easier for you to connect. (Use the locking column.) Or, of course, you can just connect any kind of Duplo block to drive the pump by hand.

Supports:

No

Notes:

Only the auger bottom parts need support.

Motor mount for the HC24 that fits 22mm mini quad motors.

The original model was made by ChaosCoreTech in ZBrush. This kind of software is ideal for sculpting models with high-level tools, but the resulting mesh is not clean, intersections of different parts can become a mess.

There were several problems with the geometry of an eyelid, the eyebrows and the intersection of the pants and the jacket. All of them have been repaired.
In addition, the center of mass has been improved by increasing the area of contact with the ground by 20%, improving the stability of the piece when standing it.
And I have also modified the geometry of the belt to make contact with the pelvis.

comments.text: The neck is incredibly fragile with a reasonable infill... could you add air tubes or something to get a more rigid structure in that area without requiring the entire print to have a higher than necessary infill?
comments.author: godoloju

comments.text: I have no problem with neck. Maybe you have layer delamination issues? As a workaround you can just add more perimeters to your model. Printing with one perimeter is a no-go for most models, regardless of geometry. I printed this model with 2 perimeters and 15%infill and it is strong enough. I also sliced it in two parts vertically and printed both laying flat.
comments.author: godoloju

comments.text:
Of course, splitting the model in two removes the problem, but I think it’s a bit extreme solution.
The problem I found was not with the neck itself but removing the supports from the neck. 3 perimeters (1.2mm with 0.4 nozzle and 1.5mm with 0.5) both of them resulted in a broken neck. But I use to print with ABS so joining parts with acetone is not a problem to me.
comments.author: 3Dpassion

comments.text: Well, in my opinion such models should only be printed in halves horisontally. If you print ABS, glueing parts back together is cery easy, 1 minutes sanding afterwards and you won’t even see the glue line. Using supports for me is the last option. I try to position models auc, so I dont have to ise supports at all. Supports are a waste of printing time and also do mot deliver smooth surface anyways.
comments.author: R3ND3R

comments.text:
I didn't mean that I would never split any model, I do split models also, it depends on the situation. Printing with ABS allows me to glue parts, to fill the gaps with ABS juice, to sand it and then melt it with acetone vapor to get professional finishes. Check out my other makes and you will see that I'm a post-process enthusiast ;)
But I don't see supports should be the last choice. It can become crucial with engineering parts and accurate dimensions. Splitting may not be the best choice printing special materials in terms of translucency, oxidation (Rick Bust patina effect would be affected by this) and so on...
comments.author: 3Dpassion

comments.text: Not my best print definitely. Used the horrible eSun PLA+ leftovers :( So decided to spray paint it. https://www.thingiverse.com/make:453046
comments.author: R3ND3R

comments.text: Yeah, I guess it's a matter of taste/choice. I personally hate using supports because I am almost never able to achieve decent finish right above them, always end up with noodle texture there, unless I use 100% PVA support, which is a whole another story :) lol.
comments.author: R3ND3R

comments.text:
Totally agree, I hate dealing with that side effect. To me, using Support Interface and playing with the values was the key to start having decent results.
Interface Thickness of 1mm and 80% Interface Density are my gold numbers, but of course I say decent, not perfect ;)
comments.author: 3Dpassion

comments.text:
You are right, the neck is very fragile, also the ankles.
I have been doing tests with internal geometries to give consistency to the area. The problem is that depending on the slicer you use, the scale of the model and the thickness of the printer's nozzle, the result varies drastically, and after a few hours testing I think the result does not provide consistency to the area nor a greater infill of the areas surrounding the air tubes, and the walls of the tubes do not connect with the outer perimeter so it won't provide strength to the area.

description.text:
This is modular desk tidy, inspired by the designs I've referenced under remix. It is however not a modification of those models, but a new original design in OpenSCAD.

This is customizable of course - if the Thingiverse customizer isn't working use a recent version of OpenSCAD (Nightly as of January 2018) with the built-in customizer capability to quickly bash out the module configurations you want.

I've included ready-generated STLs for a range of heights with lug and slot configurations that will work for any assembly. However if you want an assembly with nice flat surfaces on the visible faces, you'll need to generate your own.

I have also included a parameter file and a batch script which generate STLs for the set that is showcased in the image gallery. These files are only useful with the later version of OpenSCAD - they are of no use with OpenSCAD 2015.03-2. They can serve as a reference on how to generate your own configuration.

Printer Brand:

Wanhao

Printer:

Wanhao Duplicator i3 Plus

Resolution:

0.2

Infill:

n/a

Notes:

Very easy to print; the slot overhangs are very short and easily bridged with no support needed.

Description of how the OpenSCAD program works

This is quite a simple design in OpenSCAD.

The hexagon shapes are achieved with the $fn trick on cylinders - a cylinder made of 6 subdivisions has a hexagonal cross-section - so the main structure is a simple subtraction of an inner hexagonal cylinder from the main hexagonal cylinder.

The slots and lugs are both built the same; slots are simply a subtraction of the lug shape to create the vertical slot and the hole in the base for the mating lug to enter the module. The lug shape is a cube for the connecting bar, and a scaled cylinder (with half removed) for the lug itself.

This is a challenge my daughter and I made to create a 3d printer entirely from scratch and without buying anything. All of the parts are custom so I don't expect this will work for many other people, but I was very pleased with how quite and reliable this machine turned out to be. We had to use a lead screw on the Y axis because it's what we had and because the bed weighs about 4lbs, but with proper oiling and isolation between the aluminum parts, it's about the same volume as a Prusa MK2. Note in the video that you can still hear the titan extruder clacking around, this thing actually is surprisingly quiet. Video of it in action here https://youtu.be/o-UWYGsXUYM

The Drawer Divider Construction Set helps you organize your world. Whether for kitchen, office, or workshop you can create a custom divider for any drawer you have. You assemble standardized components into any size you want from a single section paper-clip holder to a multi-section full-drawer divider. Measure your space, design your divider, print your components, assemble your divider, and get organized today.

The components are based upon an 86mm length and width, a 51mm height, and a 3 mm thickness. You choose square bases and rectangular bases. Arrange any number of them any way you want to form a grid of bases. Then insert short and long panels between the bases, slide pillars to hold them tightly together, and put caps on the pillars to finish them off. You even have fillers strips and caps to seal base joints, unused pillar slots, and rectangular panel gaps.

Altogether, the Drawer Divider Construction Set is an open-ended general-purpose system of bases, panels, and pillars to create a wide range of drawer dividers and more. Start from here and extend it in new ways for your own uses. For example, add horizontal and vertical label holders. It's up to you and your imagination.

Technical notes: Inspiration from Elgo Skyline Building Construction Set. Design developed in FreeCAD. Pillar and caps have a single center support already in the STL files. Print panels, and filler strips with supports. Samples printed on Prusa i3 MK3 in PLA with 0.2 mm layer height. The interlock of pieces may require multiple-hands to hold pieces together while assembling. Press fit may be tight, and may require a block of wood and some "persuasion" to get it together.

Update 2018-02-20: Added Base-2x2.

I simply used PLA to print (although ABS might be better due to its slightly more flexible less brittle nature). But the PLA print has worked great i can slide the dongle out of each holder spot and click them back in (the click is very satisfying in my opinion). I do not know if this is a problem with Autodesk or Cura but you may need to scale the model up by 10 times when you load it. Hopefully this helps and comes in handy!

This is a vase I made for my orchid which was neglected far too long. I thought up the idea of making the vase look like leaves at the base of a flower. For an orchid, you don't want it told hold any water. You want to just water it once a week or so and let all the water drain out, so this vase isn't water tight. I put it in the sink and put water in it, then just leave it for an hour or so to drain before putting it back on the table.

I printed it in white ABS. Note that the bottom isn't exactly flat, so you may want to lower it slightly beneath the build surface in your slicer program to make sure the base is flat.

description.text:
To be placed on a Freeplay CM3. You also need buttons; I used Adafruit's 8mm soft tac switches, found here.

Drill 1-2mm holes just inside the screw posts for the leads to go through. Solder a pair of leads on one side to about 4" of light-gauge wire, fish through your holes, and super- or hot-glue the buttons to the GBA case's shoulders, then join to the board however you like (I did direct solder, but if you've got headers that'll fit, use those).

I made this in TinkerCAD, and you can remix it here.

BQ Witbox

Yes

0.2 mm

No

Notes:

Printed in TPU (thermoplastic polyurethane). TPU is flexible, which is a requirement of this design.

Rip out the supports

Tweezers or round-nose pliers work best for this. Grab a pair of supports, and twist, don't pull.

It's based on this thing, a GBA cart for DIY games.

For the cart cover portion, the GBA cart model was used for measurements in the construction of my own model (e.g., by placing the Z-axis through the workplane in TinkerCAD, exporting to SVG, and playing with it in Inkscape), though I did slice off and re-attach the thumb-grip.

For the actuator wings, I took several photos of the back and top of my GBA shell, and matched up the sizes to mm in Inkscape using measurements of the distance between the visible screw posts. Then, I built shapes matching what I wanted to see in those places, and booleaned them together in TinkerCAD.

description.text:
I had a stepper motor from an old printer with a press-fit timing gear already in place, so I made this pulley to adapt an M8 Greg-Wade geared extruder derivative to belt drive. I know there are other designs which are already belt drive, but I was looking for something I could make with parts I had on hand, namely 608 skate bearings and the pre-fitted timing pulley. Plus I had already been running the geared version, so the pulley was the only new component to print.
Though I did have to order in the timing belt, T2.5 - 6mm wide, 200mm long.

description.text:
Big hair, shoulderpads, it must be the 80s!

Who is that pale white lady? A vampire? A succubus?

Anyway, she's smiling so that's good!

Patrick Nagel had a distinctive style that symbolizes the 80's.

He illustrated for Playboy magazine and in 1981 his artwork was featured on Duran Duran's Rio album cover. (disclosure - not a Duran Duran fan, couldn't identify a Duran Duran song if I had to).

http://www.patricknagel.com/

Notes:

Many pieces to this model, but it can all be done on a single extruder machine with at least 200 x 200 build space. Not as simple as pushing a button and pooping out a Baby Groot, but much more satisfying.

Color - I tried to match color as closely as possible, but my filament library falls short on a few elements. In these instructions I'm relating what I did; if you have a better color scheme go for it. (you can make her face yellow and hair blue so she looks like Marge Simpson if that's your fancy.)

Outline, Joint, Hanger - Black, print x4 Outline, x7 Joint and x1 Hanger so you can hang this in your art gallery. Don't sweat if the Outline pieces are not super square, they only have to be close. 0.2 mm layers are fine.

Face, Ear, Teeth - White, change to purple (or grey/silver) at 1.1 mm, change to black at 1.2 mm. 0.1 mm layers.

Hair - Black, change to white at layer 1.1 mm, 0.1 mm layers.

Dress - What I did: started with black, changed to red at 0.9 mm, changed to purple at 1.1 mm changed to black at 1.2 mm. This made the dress darker to match the illustration. Straight red or purple would look nice too. 0.1 mm layers.

Rhombus - Beige, 0.1 mm layers.

L_earring, R_earring - Pink, 0.2 mm layers.

BKG - Light Blue, 0.2 mm layers.

Yellow slash - Yellow, 0.2 mm layers.

Green_slash - Green, 0.2 mm layers.

Lips - Black, change to red at 0.5 mm, change to white at 1.1 mm. 0.1 mm layers.

Simple fan shroud/mount to replace the original black metal heatsink fan holder. It slides over the heatsink, no screws to attach to the printer, but you have to remove the hot end from the X axis first. It fits the original fan, but I think it will work with any standard 40x40 fan. I used the same M3 bolts, just left the nuts off.

This helps keep the fan from blowing cool air on the hot end. I noticed an improvement in performance after this upgrade. My hot end heated up quicker and had less variation in temperature during prints.

Step 1: Hammer in shelf supports

I faced the rounded section down. They should hammer in quite easily.

Step 2: Insert brass inserts

I used a soldering iron. There are four holes - just pick the two that fit depending on orientation of your drawer runners.

The screws just stop the drawer runners from coming out when you pull the drawer.

Step 3: Cutout holes for the bins using a jigsaw

I created these rings to make an Olympic LED light display for the living room. 5 rings were printed - 3 solid, 2 "broken" and they were weaved to match the Olympic symbol. WS2812s were put on the inside - I used 30LED/m style so they weren't too dense. The data pins and voltage pins were joined, and code was uploaded to a ATMEGA328 chip (standard Arduino will do).

I used a 5V 8A (40W) power supply, although these should not draw more than 3.5A at peak with the code I am running. I never go full white, and even then it would be 5.4A.

Video of the lights in action:
https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=-todcTl1NH8

My code is available here:
https://github.com/thesoftwarejedi/Arduino/blob/master/olympic-leds/olympic-leds.ino
