title: Amoeba striker hop arm (nearing perfection)
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - No Derivatives

description.text:
my previous version of this was great but suffered one fatal flaw. it was wider that the barrel cut out and while it would hop nicely would not allow for the use or super heavy bbs you could wind all you wanted but it would reach a point where it would make contact with the barrel and go no further.

this version remidies this by using a simpler concave design. It is actually angled so there is the most possible contact area along the entire hop bucking ( https://gyazo.com/321564b4c86f117cf9a95333caa7896c ) and removes a sudden impact caused by the first part of the arm to contact the bb being very slightly higher than the rest of the arm (due to angles ...)

i have found even better consistency with this version than the previous iteration, however it does require more work and supports are required unfortunatly. if printed on its side there is minimal sanding required but still more than the previous version.

https://gyazo.com/895da2e3845c73a0d2861fa27b148253

UPDATE I have added 4 new versions, one with a reinforcement to the section that makes contact with the hop screw and another one that doesn't have space for a compression nub. the other 2 are the same but with contact area that protrudes out more (these 2 are untested and might be at the wrong angle)

disclaimer: this is designed for the stock hop up chamber and is not a standalone part, it requires something compressible and elastic to go between the hop screw and arm (this is true for the first 2 versions). this is designed for use with maple leaf autobot and desepticon buckings and compatible barrels. use with other brands and barrels may vary.

title: K40 Laser custom control panel - Digital + C3Dmini

description.text:
Another K40 digital panel replacement.

(Some K40's come with a potentiometer and a mA meter, others, like mine, come with a "digital" version which (I suppose) is supposed to be better, cheaper or more reliable. It isn't.)

You really need a mA meter on a K40 so you don't blow up your CO2 tube - the digital readout goes from 00.0 to 99.9 - with no units. It isn't "percent of full power", nor is it "mA" or anything except arbitrary. I needed an analog meter to determine what numbers matched the 15mA Max suggested for the K40's tube. (25.0 on the scale equates to 12 mA, and 30.0 is 15mA, at least on mine)

I was sick of the stock nano board (the one that requires a pirated version of Windows XP, a pirated version of CorelLaser and a pirated USB dongle) - even after throwing out the supplied software and using K40Whisperer (a great free program, BTW!), I wanted something better. I found it with Cohesion 3D's Mini - in a K40 upgrade friendly package. It is a smoothieboard clone, and is orders of magnitude faster than Whisperer, and is supported by the new kid on the block, Lightburn, a great layout, editing, and control software package. Aas a bonus, the C3Dmini can control lightobject's Z-table stepper with just a couple extra parts and a power supply!

Finally, I added an extra on/off switch for the power outlets, so I could turn on and off the add-on air compressor (new laser head/optics via lightobjects)

Unfortunately, I ended up with a hydra - meters and GLCD panel and an extra power switch all flailing about, causing trouble!

The end result is this design, which packs as much as possible into the old control panel's space, and does not require any case / sheet metal modifications.

The files are all the same thing, in AI, DXF and Lightburn formats.

Printer:

K40

Notes:

On the K40, with aligned mirrors and the material at the right focus depth, I used lightburn and the C3Dmini with the following settings:

6mm/s @ 100% (28 on my digital readout, 13-14mA on my meter) for cuts.
1 pass for 1/8", 2-3 passes for 1/4" acrylic or masonite
20mm/[email protected]% for the vector cut lettering

I rubbed yellow latex paint into the vector cut letters, then wiped it off the surface with a damp paper towel. "next time", I'll go slower and not wipe so hard :-)

The digital panel's button tops are below the surface of the panel, which is good (for me) as I don't want to accidentally change the settings or trigger the laser test. (The buttons were proud of the surface in a test-fit version I made using 1/8" stock, if that is what you want...)

Reproduction of the four five division insignia from The Orville (Command, Science, Engineering, Medical, Security).

Because the front and back faces are slightly curved, and not flat discs, printing them flat is not recommended. I've found it works best tilted back 15 degrees from vertical, slightly above the build plate (even a millimeter is fine), with raft and supports.

(1 March 2018 - added Science insignia.)

After printing, I gave it a couple of coats of high-build primer, then sanded it smooth using a variety of increasing grits.

Then I airbrushed the face a very light grey, let it dry, then masked off the countersunk areas (except for the "ditch" in the outer ring) with yellow Frog Tape, gave a light spray of clear coat to prevent any seepage under the edge, then airbrushed it a dark blue. Allowed that to dry, then removed the tape.

Finally, I epoxied a bit of Velcro (hook side) onto the back, for affixing it to the uniform.

Modeled in Blender.

For the Command, Engineering, Science, and Medical division badges, I worked from images posted by Joseph Porro (the costume designer) to his Pinterest page; the Security badge came from an image posted to The Orville's official Twitter feed.

The size and curvature of the insignia were estimated from various screen shots taken from the show.

This THING is to replace the key mechanism on a Stanley Hardware (may also be called a D&D Tecnologies) S836-171 CD6203 LokkLatch Deluxe Gate Latch.

To recap, the Stanley/D&D is a latching mechanism with keyed entries on both sides. On gates where both sides are equally accessible this is logical However in situations where one side is secure, having a keyed entry on that side can be a hinderance.

This THING comprises 2 parts:

Key Drum Replacment
Designed to replace the key drum on the mechanism side of the latch. In theory it could be fitted either side (mechanism or remote). It will resist pull-through but the design of the latch means push-through is a problem. (Maybe in a future release)

Key Drum Tongue
The part of the drim that engages with the mechanical toggle. Can be repl;aced with an appropriate sized piece of metal for more piece of mind.

From the author,
I was prompted to design this after accidentally locking myself out of the back door and then realising I had no keys to get through the side gates either.

This is my first 3D design (so please be gentle). It works fine (although there's a few things that I would have liked to work better. I may tune it up here and there as time goes by, we'll see.

description.text:
I've been looking for a Y-Belt tensioner for the AnyCubic i3 Mega for a long time so I finally designed my own.

The base mounts with two of the bolts for the Y-rods to avoid having to drill holes in the case to mount the base assembly. (the original M3x8 might work, but I used longer M3x12)

The idler pulley should be mountable with original screw (M5x16) and nut but it is very close. M5x18 works better. M5x20 is just a little too long and scrapes the case.

The tension bolt should be an M5 hex head cap screw, with the head going inside the carriage and the nut in the knob. I used an M5x35, but it's a little too long. M5x30 would be better.

The pulley carrier originated from https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2482051 - "Anet E10: X belt tensioner by MrCrankyface". I have added the hole for the nut and enlarged the hole for the tensioner bolt to fit M5 instead of M4. When inserting the pulley, it is very tight, but as long as you don't tighten the bolt too much it will loosen up.

History

V1 - 20180210
Issues:

  1. The bolt hole doesn't go all the way through the front pate, only half way.
  2. Printing the knob in the default orientation without supports caused some in-the-air printing for layers 38 and 39 as it transitions to the shaft.

V2 - 20180217

  • Fixed the bolt hole in the base.
  • Modified the bottom of the nut hole in the knob to make printing easier without supports
  • Chamfered the outer edge of the nut hole in the knob to make it easier to fit the nut.

description.text:
Background: I've had a few requests for a smoother DNA pencil helix and decided to do a more organic looking design using solidworks.

Print Instructions:

  1. Add both files to slicer and orient if necessary. Default orientation should work fine in most cases. Of course you can print these separately if you choose to.
  2. The part with the outer ring is the base (bottom) and the part with the inner ring is the top.
  3. Print with 20% infill and whatever layer thickness works best for you. I used 0.2mm for the pictured item.

Post Printing:

  1. Remove parts from printer

title: A6 Fan/Sensor Bracket with M12x1 threads

description.text:
This is a nearly trivial re-mix of https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2703848 which is a remix of https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2424312 I added M12x1 threads to the hole that holds the sensor.

The threads in the sensor are a very fine 1mm pitch. Having threads in the holder allows you to make actuate adjustment. for example after measuring you decide the sensor needs to by 0.25mm lower then you rotate it exactly 90 degrees and you know the exact amount you have lowered it.

Note the threads are very tight but loosen up after putting the sensor in and out a half dozen times. Hint - the sensor comes with two nuts and a lock washers. Place these on the sensor and jam them together tight. This make s good handle so you can turn the sensor into the plastic threads. Be very carful not to cross thread as it is very easy to do with these fine 1mm pitch threads

I used Fusion 360 to replace the hole in the STL file with an M12.1 threaded hole. Everything else was left alone.

I included a STEP file in case some one wants to make yet another remix

Printing: I printed the little mounting tab at the bottom, the one with the two counter sunk screw holes with 95% infill and extended this upward into the bottom frame. The rest as 40% with 1mm think top/bottom and walls this results in a very stiff and strong part

To be honest the bracket works fine with no threads

Printer:

Anet A6

Rafts:

No

Supports:

No

30% and 95% for mount tab

Notes:

Actually almost any printer setting would work.

I imported the STL file to Fusion 360, converted it to a solid object then read the hole as an M12x1 treaded hole. Saved back to STL format. The hole itself as modeled in the STEP file is now parametric and is easy to change

description.text:
I love Grimm Forest but I don't love combining cardboard tokens with amazing figurines so I made my own resource tokens. Each token has its numeric value engraved into it. You will need to print:

20 1Straw
15 1Brick
15 1Wood**

5 5Straw
5 3Brick
5 4Wood**

  • Note the manual is incorrect on the listed # of resources. This is the correct amount.

These will all fit perfectly in the insert if you are organized. See the picture for how I did it.

I sleeve all my cards and the Grimm Forest insert just won't accommodate them so I made my own card holder. There is only 12mm to work with for the card storage so I had to get very creative. When you print it you will notice there is a 0.25mm lip hanging over the cards. This is small enough that it does NOT need support to print. The lip will hold a stack of ~20 cards with the case held upside down. Slide the cards in a few at a time until each slot is full. I used the Mayday Games Premium green sleeves as pictured and measured so it is an exact 100% perfect fit. I can not promise other sleeves will work with this setup.

I hope this pack enhances your enjoyment of this great game!!

** For the wood resource token I used "A Simple Log" since it was perfect for what I needed. I shrunk it down so that 15 would fit perfectly in the token holder. I also 'welded' 4 together to produce the 4 stack. https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1453301

description.text:
This is a 3D printed press for inerting heat-set threaded inserts. It utilizes a cheap soldering iron as the heat source, a rotary dimmer to allow the user to throttle the heat output to tailor to a variety of plastics, and a drawer slider as part of the plunger assembly that pushes down onto the part.

This project was designed out of necessity while working on another big project that utilizes quite a few of these heat-set inserts. Using this press rather than just a soldering iron itself ensures that the inserts get installed accurately, with the correct temperature and in far less time.

These presses go for hundreds or even thousands of dollars so they are beyond the price range of most hobbyist, yet they are very useful in the 3D printing and DIY hobby community. I wanted to design and build a high quality and affordable unit that can be 3D printed within a few days and built for well under $100.

Please take the time to read the print settings.

What you'll need:

-1kg spool of PLA filament
-30w soldering iron similar to the one in the pictures
-Rotary dimmer switch
-Heavy-duty 12" drawer slider (ensure that the inner slide "the one that comes out" has a width of around 24.6mm)
-Assorted M4 machine screws from 6mm to 25mm in length
-M4 Nuts
-M2 self-tapping screws 8mm, 10mm, and 12mm in length
-16 gauge wire
-16 gauge electrical connectors
-6.5" light duty spring
-1-1/2" 10-24 threaded eye hooks (This holds the soldering iron to the drawer slider)
-10-24 nuts for the eye hooks
-Fender washers (These are heatsinks on the threaded eye hooks to slow down heat transfer to the plunger assembly)
-Small hose clamp to fit over the soldering iron barrel

Instructions should be available soon via Instructables. I'll post the link in here when I get around to making them. Visit the 3DAnarchy Facebook group for questions, discussion and info on this and upcoming projects: https://www.facebook.com/groups/1358672314201686/

Please remember to tip your designers. These big projects take a lot of time, money and dedication.

Printer:

Modified Flashforge Creator Pro

Rafts:

No

Supports:

No

Resolution:

0.2

Infill:

25

Notes:

-The print area must be around 280mm x 180mm. I used a modified flashforge creator pro with a large glass bed and a single extruder conversion so I designed this press around that.

-The infill should be at least 25% This press needs to be strong and sturdy. You are building one of these to last you for years so don't get cheap with the filament.

-This is best printed using PETG or PLA. I do not recommend ABS unless you are 100% sure that it will stay stuck to the print bed and wont warp since these parts are big!

-Ensure that all scale settings are set to zero in your slicer. The various holes for the screws and nuts are already designed slightly oversized so everything fits together nicely.

comments.text: Not to take away from the nice design, but when dealing with 110VAC power need to think of the end user safety. The AC power distribution boxes sold commercially are made with plastics that meet specific safety specifications. PLA does not self extinguish if there is a spark/open flame. In this case, it would be safer to integrate an UL/TUV certified distribution box.
comments.author: lgv2016

comments.text: I can see this being a valid concern but since the distribution bus is only used to fasten two electrical connectors (which are safety rated to handle current) tightly to each other I think the risk is very minimal.
comments.author: lgv2016

comments.text: Agreed. As long as potential users are informed and understand the risks.

description.text:
This adapter connects an aircraft map light socket to 1" RAM Mount hardware. (Shout out to RAM Mounts for their excellent hardware!) The nominal size of the sockets is 3/8" (0.375) but every aircraft has worn differently. Hence, the multiple size.

You will need a machine screw and nut to finish this. I also recommend threadlocker.

My best results where with PET because of its excellent layer adhesion and sheer resistance. ABS split on the layer lines when people torqued the ball. This turned it into an uncontrollable swivel - whomp whomp. PET didn't have this problem. I wouldn't recommend PLA since cockpits can get pretty hot and might lead to warpage/seapage.

description.text:
Three different housing for USB ports. I need these for self-soldered USB plugs and cables for heavy loads and device testing (chargers, solar panels, cable testing, etc.). See here: https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2789320

The thin cable version is for approx. 4.5 mm thick cables, the thick for 5.5 mm cables. You can print them with flex filament to have a nice and tight fit (see the two at the bottom of the first picture). If the cables are too thick or you can not remove the mounted connectors, use the split version and glue them together with superglue. I printed all versions in Colorfabb NGEN and NGEN Flex, but will work with any filament. Print them upright as the stl-files are positioned and mount with logo on the top.

Solderable USB ports are available from Panstrong, Confly, and other manufacturers.

Added a case for Female breakout adapters as well. See pictures and STL-files. I don't know from which place I ordered them some time ago.

Enjoy!

title: Moto G5 Plus phone stand
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text:
This is a stand on which to attach Lenovo Moto G5 Plus Wall Holder ( https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2514831), so the result looks better than the phone stand I was using at work.

It holds the phone at 60 degrees, but you can customise the angle if your tastes differ. The uprights should move themselves to join to the top of the mount.

You'll need a couple of M3 10mm screws. Pre-thread the holes to make mounting easier.

I've glued a micro-SD cable for charging the phone, having made it easy to lift the phone out (remove the little tabs on the plug).

The stand itself isn't heavy enough on its own for one-handed pickup of the phone, so I've glued it to a stone plinth. Any metal of a size similar to the base plate will do.

Not pictured: the holder itself. My phone has no case, so a strip of leather glued to the holder back allows the phone a smooth entry and exit. As well, I've dremelled a gap for the headphone socket.

title: Cylindrical Desiccant Container
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text:
I disliked the desiccant container designs out there because none of them made use of the bridging ability of FDM Printers.

A relatively simple desiccant container that has a lot of very fine slits for air circulation (more than 4000 slits).

Each slit has an height of 3 times the layer height, in this case 0,6 mm and an approximate width of 8mm.

Print time on my i3 mk3 was about 5~6 hours.

This is supposed to be printed with the Prusa i3 (Mk3) 0.20 mm Profile and sliced with Slic3r, other Slicers and Profiles might work alright to, if interest prevails I might cleanup the scad file and/or make other versions optimized for different slicing profiles.

The lid is snug and will hold when the container is turned upside down, it can be inserted more easily when it is turned one half-angel step, and then turned back so that all the notches are in the slits. (Just play around with it)

title: Mad Max: Fury Road - Nux Bird Bobble Head

description.text:
I've always loved the little bird dashboard bobble head that Nux has in Mad Max: Fury Road. I just got a 3D printer and on searching for files for this one, found there was nothing (at least that I could find). So I decided to make my own version!

It's not 100% movie accurate but it's close enough for me to look at and go "YEAH! That's rad!" haha.

Enjoy!

Building historic on the Fury Road!

I used the Raven Skull by sprocket1597 and modelled the rest with TinkerCAD. I ended up splitting the skull so the beak parts printed pretty much upright and it printed fine with just a small brim.

The spring is a number C-766 (9/16 x 3 x .054, 14.300 x 76.2 x 1.372) by Century Spring Corp. I bought it from Bunnings here in Australia. It took a little squishing at the top to fit into the hole I modelled, and I had to cut it down as it was quite long, but I'm happy with the results and it bobbles well! The spring is stuck down in the stand well with some kneadable mending epoxy stuff I stuffed down in there and jammed the spring into.

I painted it with flat soft iron and satin ivory spray paint and then did a diluted black wash and rub to dirty it up.

https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2277417
and https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:27626
I bought a Tronxy X5S printer and mounted this extruder on the top back right corner. Up side down to get it to feed the same direction as the original extruder :) and drilled the hole for the filament to fit a bowden tube nut/clamp.
Original Stepper motor (Nema17).
New steel hob-gear (slightly bigger then the brass one that came with the printer).
2 of the original Tronxy idler bearings reused for the big gear axle/shaft.
I have not yet upgraded the firmware and running the X5S as original. Updated the start g-code with M92 E440 instead of M92 E100 worked fine for me (remember to power cycle the printer after changing). I´m also laborating with coasting and restart distance to get the starting point better now when the extruder feeds witout delays or skipping.
The mount is designed to fit the Tronxy X5S but will probably also fit other printers made of 2020 or 2040 aluminium profiles. Tagging CR10 since that model also seem to come with a simple (high skip rate) extruder.

Bitcoin is a cryptocurrency and worldwide payment system. It is the first decentralized digital currency, as the system works without a central bank or single administrator. The network is peer-to-peer and transactions take place between users directly, without an intermediary. These transactions are verified by network nodes through the use of cryptography and recorded in a public distributed ledger called a blockchain. Bitcoin was invented by an unknown person or group of people under the name Satoshi Nakamoto and released as open-source software in 2009.

description.text: Anet logo

A simple snap-in plug for a 32mm hole in the bottom of a Piggybank. The scad-script is made for a material thickness of around 4mm and with a bit of tolerance to allow for a layer of varnish or paint.

Play around with the tolerances in the script for a good, tight fit, vs. ease to remove the plug.

I have printed loads of these in PLA. and most of mine are so flexible that the pins won't break when removing and inserting the plug, but do test it out, as I have experienced that at least one of the PLAs I had turned very brittle after printing.
